            "content": "# v0.5 Milestone Plan: Sneakernet Export\n\n**Date:** 2026-03-27\n**Milestone:** v0.5 — Sneakernet Export\n**Status:** Planning\n\n---\n\n## Scope decisions\n\n- **QR codes**: Deferred to v0.5.1 or later. v0.5 is file-based only.\n- **Archive format**: Opaque bundles — versioned header + length-prefixed WirePayload frames. No cleartext metadata beyond version and count.\n- **CLI design**: Subcommand infrastructure — `reme` (default) = TUI, `reme export ...`, `reme import ...`.\n- **Tech debt**: Cherry-pick only blocking bugs (#99, #97, #98).\n- **Batch submit API**: New `POST /api/v1/submit-batch` endpoint for multi-envelope submission, reducing round-trips when importing bundles on connected nodes.\n\n---\n\n## Issue decomposition\n\n### Layer 0: Bug fixes (no dependencies, can start immediately)\n\n#### Issue A: fix: `send_text_tiered` blocks TUI event loop (#99)\n\n**Existing issue.** Assign to v0.5 milestone.\n\n`send_text_tiered()` is called synchronously from the TUI event handler, blocking rendering during network I/O. Needs to be moved to a background task with status feedback.\n\nDirectly affects export UX — if the TUI freezes during normal sends, it'll freeze during export operations too.\n\n#### Issue B: fix: tombstone send blocks TUI rendering (#97)\n\n**Existing issue.** Assign to v0.5 milestone.\n\nSame pattern as #99 — tombstone submission blocks the event loop. Move to background task.\n\n#### Issue C: fix: embedded node `run()` exits immediately (#98)\n\n**Existing issue.** Assign to v0.5 milestone.\n\nThe embedded HTTP server's `run()` method returns immediately after binding, so the server task can be dropped before it serves any requests. Affects local import reliability — if someone imports a bundle while the embedded node is supposed to relay, it might not be running.\n\n---\n\n### Layer 1: Foundation (no dependencies between each other)\n\n#### Issue 1: `reme-bundle` crate — archive format and implementation\n\n**New crate:** `crates/reme-bundle/`\n\n**Archive format (`.reme` bundle):**\n\n```\n[magic: 4 bytes \"REME\"]\n[format_version: u8]       // 1\n[flags: u8]                // reserved, 0 for now\n[frame_count: u32 LE]     // number of WirePayload frames\n[frames: repeated]\n  [frame_len: u32 LE]     // byte length of this frame\n  [frame: WirePayload bytes]  // type discriminator + postcard payload\n[checksum: 32 bytes]       // BLAKE3 hash of all preceding bytes\n```\n\nDesign rationale:\n- Fixed magic bytes for file-type detection\n- Version byte for future format evolution\n- Frame count upfront so readers can pre-allocate\n- Length-prefixed frames (not self-delimiting postcard) for robustness — a corrupt frame doesn't break the rest\n- BLAKE3 checksum for integrity verification (not authentication — the envelopes themselves are authenticated)\n- Little-endian fixed-width integers for simplicity (no varint — bundle metadata isn't bandwidth-constrained like wire format)\n\n**Public API:**\n\n```rust\npub struct BundleWriter<W: Write> { ... }\nimpl<W: Write> BundleWriter<W> {\n    pub fn new(writer: W) -> Self;\n    pub fn write_frame(&mut self, wire_payload: &[u8]) -> Result<(), BundleError>;\n    pub fn finish(self) -> Result<(), BundleError>;  // writes checksum\n}\n\npub struct BundleReader<R: Read> { ... }\nimpl<R: Read> BundleReader<R> {\n    pub fn open(reader: R) -> Result<Self, BundleError>;  // validates magic + version\n    pub fn frame_count(&self) -> u32;\n    pub fn next_frame(&mut self) -> Result<Option<Vec<u8>>, BundleError>;\n    pub fn verify_checksum(&mut self) -> Result<(), BundleError>;\n}\n\npub struct BundleMetadata {\n    pub format_version: u8,\n    pub flags: u8,\n    pub frame_count: u32,\n}\n```\n\n**Dependencies:** `reme-message` (for `WirePayload::decode` validation), `blake3`, `thiserror`.\n\n**Tests:**\n- Round-trip: write N frames → read N frames, verify identical\n- Corrupt magic → error\n- Corrupt checksum → error\n- Truncated file → error\n- Empty bundle (0 frames) → valid\n- Large bundle (10k frames) → works\n- Fuzz harness for `BundleReader::open`\n\n**Acceptance criteria:**\n- `cargo test -p reme-bundle` passes\n- Bundle format documented in `spec/archive-format.md`\n- Fuzz target added\n\n**Blocked by:** nothing\n**Blocks:** Issue 3 (export), Issue 4 (import), Issue 6 (batch submit)\n\n---\n\n#### Issue 2: Restructure client binary with clap subcommands\n\n**Files:** `apps/client/src/main.rs`, `apps/client/src/config.rs`\n\nIntroduce `clap::Subcommand` to the client binary:\n\n```rust\n#[derive(Parser)]\n#[command(name = \"reme\")]\nstruct Cli {\n    #[command(subcommand)]\n    command: Option<Commands>,\n\n    // Global args (shared across subcommands)\n    #[arg(short = 'd', long, env = \"REME_DATA_DIR\")]\n    data_dir: Option<PathBuf>,\n    #[arg(short = 'c', long, env = \"REME_CONFIG\")]\n    config: Option<PathBuf>,\n    #[arg(short = 'l', long, env = \"REME_LOG_LEVEL\")]\n    log_level: Option<String>,\n}\n\n#[derive(Subcommand)]\nenum Commands {\n    /// Launch the interactive TUI (default when no subcommand given)\n    Tui(TuiArgs),\n    /// Export pending messages to a .reme bundle file\n    Export(ExportArgs),\n    /// Import messages from a .reme bundle file\n    Import(ImportArgs),\n}\n```\n\n`Option<Commands>` with `None` defaulting to TUI preserves backward compatibility — running bare `reme` still launches the TUI.\n\nMove TUI-specific args (`--http-url`, `--mqtt-url`, `--outbox-*`, etc.) into `TuiArgs`. Keep global args (data dir, config, log level) on the parent `Cli`.\n\n**Acceptance criteria:**\n- `reme` → launches TUI (unchanged behavior)\n- `reme tui` → same\n- `reme export --help` → shows export options (stub implementation)\n- `reme import --help` → shows import options (stub implementation)\n- All existing CLI args continue working\n- `cargo test -p client` passes\n\n**Blocked by:** nothing\n**Blocks:** Issue 3 (export), Issue 4 (import)\n\n---\n\n### Layer 2: Core commands (depend on Layer 1)\n\n#### Issue 3: `reme export` CLI subcommand\n\n**Depends on:** Issue 1 (reme-bundle), Issue 2 (subcommands)\n\n```\nreme export [OPTIONS] <FILE>\n\nArguments:\n  <FILE>  Output path for the .reme bundle\n\nOptions:\n  --to <PUBLIC_ID>   Export only messages for this recipient\n  --all              Export all pending outbox messages (default)\n  --include-sent     Include messages already confirmed (re-export)\n```\n\n**Implementation:**\n\n1. Load config and open storage (reuse existing config loading from TUI path)\n2. Query outbox: `outbox_get_pending()` or `outbox_get_for_recipient()`\n3. For each `PendingMessage`: encode `envelope_bytes` as `WirePayload::Message` frame\n4. Also export pending tombstones if any: encode as `WirePayload::AckTombstone` frames\n5. Write bundle via `BundleWriter`\n6. Print summary: `Exported N messages (M tombstones) to <file>`\n\n**Edge cases:**\n- No pending messages → print \"Nothing to export\" and exit 0\n- File already exists → error unless `--force`\n- Invalid recipient pubid → error with helpful message\n\n**Acceptance criteria:**\n- `reme export out.reme` creates valid bundle with all pending messages\n- `reme export --to <pubid> out.reme` filters to one recipient\n- Bundle is valid (passes `BundleReader::verify_checksum`)\n- Export does not modify outbox state (non-destructive)\n- Integration test with TestServer\n\n**Blocked by:** Issue 1, Issue 2\n**Blocks:** Issue 5 (TUI), Issue 7 (integration tests)\n\n---\n\n#### Issue 4: `reme import` CLI subcommand\n\n**Depends on:** Issue 1 (reme-bundle), Issue 2 (subcommands)\n\n```\nreme import <FILE>\n\nArguments:\n  <FILE>  Path to a .reme bundle file to import\n```\n\n**Implementation:**\n\n1. Open bundle via `BundleReader::open()`\n2. Verify checksum\n3. For each frame:\n   a. `WirePayload::decode(bytes)` → determine type\n   b. For `Message(OuterEnvelope)`:\n      - Check if `routing_key` matches our own → process as incoming message via `Client::process_message()`\n      - Otherwise → attempt delivery via configured transports (submit to outbox for relay)\n   c. For `AckTombstone`:\n      - Process via existing tombstone handling\n4. Deduplication: check `message_id` against storage before processing\n5. Print summary: `Imported N messages (M skipped as duplicates, K relayed)`\n\n**Deduplication strategy:**\n- Check `messages` table for existing `message_id` before inserting\n- Check outbox for existing `message_id` before re-enqueuing\n- Skip silently on duplicate (idempotent import)\n\n**Edge cases:**\n- Corrupt bundle → error with frame number that failed\n- Unknown WirePayload type → skip with warning (forward compat)\n- Message for unknown routing key → relay via outbox if transports configured, skip otherwise\n\n**Acceptance criteria:**\n- `reme import bundle.reme` processes all frames\n- Duplicate import is idempotent (no double messages)\n- Messages for self are decrypted and stored in conversation\n- Messages for others are relayed via outbox\n- Corrupt bundle produces clear error\n\n**Blocked by:** Issue 1, Issue 2\n**Blocks:** Issue 5 (TUI), Issue 7 (integration tests)\n\n---\n\n#### Issue 6: Batch submit API endpoint (`POST /api/v1/submit-batch`)\n\n**Depends on:** Issue 1 (reme-bundle — reuse frame format)\n\nAdd a batch submission endpoint to the node API that accepts multiple WirePayload frames in a single HTTP request. Reduces round-trips when a node imports a bundle and needs to forward messages to connected nodes.\n\n**Endpoint:**\n\n```\nPOST /api/v1/submit-batch\nContent-Type: application/octet-stream\nBody: [count: u32 LE][frame_len: u32 LE][frame]...[frame_len: u32 LE][frame]\n```\n\nReuses the same length-prefixed frame format as the bundle (without magic, version, or checksum — those are file-level concerns). Alternatively, the body could be a complete `.reme` bundle, but a simpler framing without file metadata is more appropriate for an API.\n\n**Implementation:**\n\n1. Parse count and frames from body\n2. Validate count against a configurable max (default: 100, prevents abuse)\n3. For each frame: process identically to existing `submit_payload()` handler\n4. Rate limiting: count each frame as one request against the existing per-IP rate limit\n5. Return summary response: `{ \"accepted\": N, \"rejected\": M, \"errors\": [...] }`\n6. Transactional: process all-or-nothing? No — best-effort, report per-frame results\n\n**Node-core changes:**\n- Add `submit_batch()` to `MailboxStore` trait that wraps multiple inserts in a single SQLite transaction (performance)\n- Existing `submit_payload()` remains for single-message compat\n\n**Transport trait extension:**\n- Add `submit_messages(&self, envelopes: &[OuterEnvelope]) -> Vec<Result<(), TransportError>>` with default implementation that loops over `submit_message()` (backward compat)\n- `HttpTransport` overrides to use batch endpoint when available (feature detection via `/health` version or fail-and-fallback)\n\n**Body size limit:** Configurable, default 2 MiB (vs 256 KiB for single submit). This allows ~50-100 typical messages per batch.\n\n**Acceptance criteria:**\n- `POST /api/v1/submit-batch` accepts and processes multiple envelopes\n- Rate limiting counts per-frame\n- Batch of 50 messages is faster than 50 individual POSTs\n- Single-message submit still works unchanged\n- Replication propagates batch-submitted messages normally\n- Integration test with batch of 10 messages\n\n**Blocked by:** nothing (can start independently, but Issue 1 informs frame format)\n**Blocks:** nothing (import can work without it initially, using per-message submit)\n\n---\n\n### Layer 3: UX (depends on Layer 2)\n\n#### Issue 5: TUI integration for sneakernet export/import\n\n**Depends on:** Issue 3 (export), Issue 4 (import)\n\nAdd export/import flows to the TUI for users who prefer the interactive interface.\n\n**Keybindings:**\n- `Alt+E` / `F6` → Export popup\n- `Alt+L` / `F7` → Import popup\n\n**Export popup:**\n- Shows count of pending messages (total and per-contact)\n- Text input for file path (default: `~/reme-export-{timestamp}.reme`)\n- Option to filter by current conversation contact\n- Progress indicator during export\n- Success/error message\n\n**Import popup:**\n- Text input for file path\n- Progress indicator during import\n- Summary: N imported, M duplicates skipped, K relayed\n- Error details if any frames failed\n\n**Implementation:** Follow existing popup pattern (`show_*_popup` bool + `handle_*_popup_key_event()` + render in `ui.rs`).\n\n**Acceptance criteria:**\n- Alt+E opens export popup, exports to specified file\n- Alt+L opens import popup, imports from specified file\n- Progress feedback during operations\n- Error states handled gracefully (file not found, corrupt bundle, etc.)\n- Help text (Alt+H) updated with new shortcuts\n\n**Blocked by:** Issue 3, Issue 4\n**Blocks:** nothing\n\n---\n\n### Layer 4: Documentation and testing\n\n#### Issue 7: Integration tests for sneakernet round-trip\n\n**Depends on:** Issue 3 (export), Issue 4 (import)\n\nEnd-to-end tests validating the complete sneakernet workflow.\n\n**Test scenarios:**\n1. **Happy path:** Alice sends to Bob → export → file transfer → Bob imports → message appears in Bob's storage\n2. **Relay path:** Alice exports messages for Charlie → Bob imports → Bob's outbox relays to Charlie via HTTP\n3. **Round-trip integrity:** Export → import → re-export → compare bundles (byte-identical)\n4. **Duplicate resilience:** Import same bundle twice → no duplicate messages\n5. **Mixed content:** Bundle with both messages and tombstones → both processed correctly\n6. **Empty bundle:** Export with no pending messages → valid empty bundle → import is no-op\n7. **Large bundle:** 100+ messages → export/import completes without errors\n\n**Property tests (proptest):**\n- For any sequence of valid OuterEnvelopes: export → import preserves all envelopes exactly\n- For any valid bundle: import is idempotent\n\n**Acceptance criteria:**\n- All scenarios pass\n- No message loss or corruption in any test\n- Tests run in CI (no external dependencies)\n\n**Blocked by:** Issue 3, Issue 4\n**Blocks:** nothing\n\n---\n\n#### Issue 8: Document archive format specification\n\n**File:** `spec/archive-format.md`\n\nFormal specification of the `.reme` bundle format for interoperability. This is an explicit ROADMAP deliverable (\"Archive format documented for interoperability\").\n\n**Contents:**\n- Format overview and design rationale\n- Byte-level format specification\n- Frame types (message, tombstone)\n- Checksum algorithm\n- Version evolution strategy\n- Example bundles (hex dumps)\n- Security properties (what's protected, what's not)\n\n**Acceptance criteria:**\n- Spec is sufficient for an independent implementation to produce/consume compatible bundles\n- At least one hex-dump example with annotated fields\n- Security section explicitly states: bundle integrity (checksum), no confidentiality of metadata (routing keys visible in frames), message confidentiality preserved (E2E encryption)\n\n**Blocked by:** Issue 1 (format must be finalized)\n**Blocks:** nothing\n\n---\n\n## Dependency graph\n\n```\nLayer 0 (bugs):     #99  #97  #98        (independent, no deps)\n                      |    |    |\nLayer 1 (foundation): Issue 1 (bundle)   Issue 2 (subcommands)\n                        |    \\              |\n                        |     \\-------------|-------\\\nLayer 2 (commands):  Issue 3 (export)   Issue 4 (import)   Issue 6 (batch API)\n                        |    \\              |\n                        |     \\-------------|\nLayer 3 (UX):        Issue 5 (TUI integration)\n                        |                   |\nLayer 4 (docs/test): Issue 7 (integration)  Issue 8 (spec doc)\n```\n\nIssue 6 (batch API) is independent of the export/import chain — it can be developed in parallel. It enhances import performance but is not required for basic functionality.\n\n---\n\n## Milestone success criteria (from ROADMAP)\n\n- [x] Round-trip export → USB → import works correctly\n- [ ] QR codes work for messages up to ~500 bytes — **deferred to v0.5.1**\n- [x] Archive format documented for interoperability\n- [x] No data loss or corruption in transfer\n\n## Out of scope for v0.5\n\n- QR code generation/scanning (deferred to v0.5.1)\n- Compression (postcard encoding is already compact)\n- Bundle encryption (envelopes are already E2E encrypted)\n- Bundle signing (checksum provides integrity; authentication is per-envelope)\n- Streaming import (process-as-you-read vs read-all-then-process) — premature optimization\n",
